    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix double-free and use-after-free in EIA2 integrity context handling\n\n### Summary\nThe EIA2 integrity functions in nas_stream_eia2.c had critical memory management issues due to casting between incompatible structure types. This caused crashes and memory corruption when stream_integrity_free_eia2() was called.\n\nThe issue occurred because cbc_cmac_ctx_t (32 bytes) was being cast to stream_security_context_t (8 bytes) and back, which is undefined behavior in C. Under memory pressure or with certain compiler optimizations, this led to segfaults in free_aes_128_cbc_cmac().\n\n### Changes\n- `openair3/SECU/nas_stream_eia2.c`: \n  * Fixed stream_integrity_init_eia2() to properly allocate separate stream_security_context_t and cbc_cmac_ctx_t structures\n  * Updated nas_stream_encrypt_eia2() to access context through stream_cipher->context->context\n  * Enhanced stream_integrity_free_eia2() with NULL checks to prevent double-free\n\n### Reproduction\nThe issue can be reproduced by:\n1. Initializing EIA2 integrity context with stream_integrity_init_eia2()\n2. Using it for integrity protection with nas_stream_encrypt_eia2() \n3. Calling stream_integrity_free_eia2() - this may segfault or corrupt heap metadata\n4. Under valgrind, \"Invalid read\" and \"Invalid free\" errors are reported\n\nIn some cases, subsequent allocations would return pointers to already-freed memory regions, causing silent data corruption in other parts of the application.\n"
}